  "local_port": 52022,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "If I connect USB OTG pendrive to my power bank and connect the other point with data cable to my mobile, will pendrive be working on my mobile?",
  "response": "Connecting a USB OTG pendrive to your power bank and then linking the power bank to your mobile via a data cable **will not** allow the pendrive to work on your mobile. Here's why:\n\n### Key Reasons:\n1. **Power Bank Functionality**: \n   - Power banks are designed to **supply power**, not to transfer data. Their USB ports typically lack data-line connections, meaning they can't act as a bridge between the pendrive and your mobile.\n\n2. **USB OTG Requirements**:\n   - For a mobile to read a pendrive via USB OTG, the **mobile must act as the host**. This requires the pendrive to be connected **directly to the mobile** (using an OTG adapter or compatible port). The power bank cannot facilitate this host-device relationship.\n\n3. **No Data Passthrough**:\n   - Even if the power bank has multiple ports, they usually operate independently for charging. Data signals from the pendrive won\u2019t route through the power bank to your mobile.\n\n### Exceptions (Unlikely Scenarios):\n   - If your power bank has a **built-in USB hub with data passthrough** (rare), it *might* work. However, most power banks lack this feature.\n   - Ensure the data cable and mobile port support OTG (some cables/ports are power-only).\n\n### Solution:\nTo use the pendrive with your mobile:\n1. **Connect the pendrive directly to your mobile** using a USB OTG adapter.\n2. If you need simultaneous charging, use a **USB OTG hub** that allows connecting both the pendrive and a charger to your mobile.\n\nIn your current setup, the pendrive remains undetected because the data path is not established through the power bank.",
